Good Morning Five police officers guarding embattled Migori Governor Okoth Obado had their firearms confiscated at the weekend as DCI probes guns recovered from Obados home in Migori. The Administration officers were directed to hand over their guns for ballistic examination at the DCI headquarters, Kiambu road.Here are the stories making headlines in the Star this Monday morning. MPs want to determine their own salaries through PSC, kick out SRC Members of the National Assembly are hatching plans to determine and review their own salaries by barring the Salaries and Remuneration Commission from regularly regulating their income. Through the Parliamentary Service Bill 2018, the lawmakers want to edge out SRC and mandate the Parliamentary Service Commission to decide how much they earn. Clause 33 of the Bill states: “The employees of the Commission shall be paid such remuneration and allowances as shall be determined by the Commission”. MPs: Ruto wants to bring Congo maize Three Rift Valley MPs have triggered a political storm after publicly claiming Deputy President William Ruto has a 500,000-acre farm in the Republic of Congo. In a scathing attack on the DP, the rebel Jubilee lawmakers claimed Ruto was positioning himself to be the principal maize supplier to the scandal-ridden National Cereals and Produce Board by discouraging the region from maize farming. MPs Joshua Kutuny (Cherangany), Alfred Keter (Nandi Hill) and Silas Tiren (Moiben) claimed Ruto has been encouraging farmers to substitute maize farming with avocado and macadamia. _____________________________________________________ Uhuru, Ruto backs two thirds gender rule President Uhuru Kenyatta has asked MPs to pass the tow thirds gender rule set to be tabled in the National Assembly on Tuesday. Uhuru told legislators to ensure that they act accordingly and implement fully the constitution by passing the bill that has been sponsored by Majority Leader in the National Assembly Aden Duale. Separately, Deputy President William Ruto has told MPs to put their selfish interests aside and support the third Gender rule which will see more women in Parliament. Ruto said that women and girls comprise half of the Kenyan population and so it was wrong for them to remain out of leadership. _____________________________________________________ Mothers ignorant of Linda Mama miss out on free delivery services It is 11 o’clock in the morning. Four women are seated in the blazing sun outside an iron sheet house, in one of their homesteads in Nginye community, Kajiado county. Among them is Gladys Saningo, 32, who excuses herself to go attend to her month-old baby. We discuss as she changes her baby’s napkins before breastfeeding her. Gladys has four children aged between one month and 10 years old. She has been delivering them at home, apart from her third-born child. This, she says, is a combination of culture, poor infrastructure and being unable to contain labour for long. _____________________________________________________ Over 800 illegal clinics to be shut down in Nairobi At least 800 private clinics in Nairobi risk being closed after they were identified to be operating illegally. According to a report by the Nairobi County Public Health Department, the clinics lack the required documentation and permits. In August last year, a mapping program was conducted by the health department, which discovered the county had a total of 2,315 private clinics. _____________________________________________________ Thiong’o’s seminal novel, ‘Matigari’, to be adapted into a film Celebrated Kenyan writer Ngugi wa Thiong’o's novel Matigari, is being adapted to a film by Nollywood director Kunle Afolayan. Kunle is a Nigerian actor, film producer and director. His work has received universal acclaim and was the first Nigerian film to be screened at the Pan African Film Festival in 2007. _____________________________________________________ For more on these stories and others, keep browsing the 